  "slug": "hand-pies-sour-cherry",
  "title": "Sour cherry hand pies",
  "subtitle": "Small hand-held pastry pies with a jammy cherry filling",
  "excerpt": "Small, half-moon pastry pies filled with a thick sour cherry filling and sealed at the edge with a crimp before baking. The pastry is an all-butter shortcrust; the filling is made from sour cherries cooked briefly with sugar until jammy and glossy. The hand size format means no tin is needed: they are formed on a lined baking tray and hold their own shape.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Small hand-held pastry pies filled with fruit are documented in British and American baking literature from at least the eighteenth century. Hannah Glasse, The Art of Cookery Made Plain and Easy (1747, public domain and available at Project Gutenberg), describes small pastry cases filled with fruit. The sour cherry filling variant is described in American and British domestic baking guides from the early twentieth century, with sour cherries commonly used as a pie filling in these traditions.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The filling must be fully cooled before it goes into the pastry: a warm filling softens the dough and makes the pies difficult to seal and transfer to the tray. Make the filling the day before if convenient. The ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "fork crimp at the edge",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "term": "Crimping hand pies",
                  "termId": "cmppnmmau000018v4ji3zxeft"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " is both decorative and functional: press firmly so the seal holds. Cut a small steam vent in the top of each pie before baking.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
